body:
If we want to read values of some signals, as presented by the example in verilator documentation, firstly we need to add comment behind the signal name: 

```
module our #(
     parameter WIDTH = 32
  ) (input clk);
     reg [WIDTH-1:0] readme   /*verilator public_flat_rd*/;
     reg [WIDTH-1:0] writeme;
     initial $finish;
  endmodule

```

And then read its value in the C++ wrapper:

```
vpiHandle vh1 = vpi_handle_by_name((PLI_BYTE8*)"TOP.our.readme", NULL);
     
if (!vh1) vl_fatal(__FILE__, __LINE__, "sim_main", "No handle found");
     
s_vpi_value v;
v.format = vpiIntVal;
vpi_get_value(vh1, &v);
printf("Value of readme: %d\n", v.value.integer); 
```

This is an example of reading one signal. Is there any way to automatically add the comment `/*verilator public_flat_rd*/` behind all the signals in all the modules in a design, by signals I refer to all input and output ports and all internally defined `logic` (say in SystemVerilog) signals. More than that, automatically create a vpi handle for all these signals and read the value,  as in  `vpi_get_value(vh1, &v)`.

If not, does it mean one currently can only do this by hand and go through the signals of a design one by one?
